&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The regular expression `[^afg]` matches any character that isn&#39;t one of those three letters. You can create a regexp dynamically from the array, and then replace that.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let myArr = [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;f&#39;, &#39;g&#39;];
    let re = new RegExp(&#39;[^&#39; + myArr.join(&#39;&#39;) + &#39;]&#39;, &#39;g&#39;);
    let string = &#39;the quick brown fox jumped over the lazy dog&#39;;
    console.log(string.replace(re, &#39;*&#39;));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

without regexps:

    const allowed = new Set([&#39;a&#39;, &#39;f&#39;, &#39;g&#39;]);
    input.split(&#39;&#39;).map(x =&gt; allowed.has(x) ? x : &#39;*&#39;).join(&#39;&#39;)

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const input = &quot;abcdefghijklmnop&quot;;
    const allowed = new Set([&#39;a&#39;, &#39;f&#39;, &#39;g&#39;]);
    console.log(input.split(&#39;&#39;).map(x =&gt; allowed.has(x) ? x : &#39;*&#39;).join(&#39;&#39;));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

    input.split(&#39;&#39;)

can be replaced with

    [...input]

in ES6

Here&#39;s a non-regExp way that uses `Array.map()`

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let myArr = [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;f&#39;, &#39;g&#39;];
    let string = &#39;the quick brown fox jumped over the lazy dog&#39;;

