Interested if this can be done in **JavaScript** without a callback, I came up with

    str = str.replace(/^(\w+\W+\w+\W+\b)\w?|(?!^)(\W*)\w/gy, &#39;$1$2*&#39;);

[See this demo at regex101][1]

The idea might look a bit confusing but it seems to work fine. It should fail on one or two words but start as soon, as there appears a word character after the first two words. Important to use the [sticky flag `y`][2] which is similar to the `\G` anchor (continue on last match) but always is bound to start.

To not add an additional asterisk, the ...`\b)\w?`... part after the first two words is essential. The [word boundary][3] will force a third word to start but the first [capturing group][4] is closed after `\b` and the first character of the third word will be consumed but not captured to correctly match the asterisk count.

The second capturing group on the right side of the alternation will capture any optional *non word characters* appearing between any words after the third one.

